A study seeking to shed light on divorced women, their needs, and reasons for the crisis that led them to seek a divorce revealed another side of the problem. A study conducted by Dr Khalid AlSayed of the Shaikh Khalifa Bin Zayed AlNahyan College of Health Sciences, Qatar University and a team of researchers from Mansoura University in Egypt explored the rationale of women’s divorce seeking, and the consequences inflicted upon their personal wellbeing and satisfaction. The data were drawn from a survey conducted on the female population of Doha. The researchers identified divorced women’s characteristics, experiences, and their needs to develop ways of helping women overcome marital problems. They explored the tools used by preceding studies to assess people’s self-perception and satisfaction. Dr AlSayed says: “I believe that marital crisis is the result of several factors that need to be systematically identified, including acculturation issues, misunderstandings, communication problems, and immigration-related difficulties.” “In my study, I found that a divorced woman in Qatar finds it hard to deal with her children during divorce proceedings. She finds it difficult to find a spouse who will take care of her and her children after divorce. She is also concerned about financial and housing security.
